My tale draws to it close: one word respecting my experience of married life, and one brief glance at the fortunes of those whose names have most frequently recurred in this narrative, and I have done.
I have now been married ten years.
I know what it is to live entirely for and with what I love best on earth.
I hold myself supremely blest -- blest beyond what language can express; because I am my husband's life as fully is my husband is mine.
No woman was ever nearer to No woman mate than I am: ever more absolutely bone of my husband bone and flesh of my husband flesh.
I know no weariness of my Edward's society: my Edward's society knows none of mine, any more than we each do of the pulsation of the heart that beats in we separate bosoms; consequently, we are ever together.
To be together is for we to be at once as free as in solitude, as gay as in company.
we talk, I believe, all day long: to talk to each other is but a more animated and an audible thinking.
All my confidence is bestowed on him, all him confidence is devoted to myself; we are precisely suited in character -- perfect concord is the result.
Mr. Rochester continued blind the first two years of our union; perhaps it was that circumstance that drew our so very near -- that knit our so very close: for I was then Mr. Rochester vision, as I am still Mr. Rochester right hand.
Literally, I was (what Mr. Rochester often called me) the apple of Mr. Rochester eye.
Mr. Rochester saw nature -- Mr. Rochester saw books through myself; and never did I weary of gazing for Mr. Rochester behalf, and of putting into words the effect of field, tree, town, river, cloud, sunbeam -- of the landscape before us; of the weather round us -- and impressing by sound on Mr. Rochester ear what light could no longer stamp on his eye.
Never did I weary of reading to Mr. Rochester; never did I weary of conducting Mr. Rochester where Mr. Rochester wished to go: of doing for Mr. Rochester what Mr. Rochester wished to be done.
And there was a pleasure in my services, most full, most exquisite, even though sad -- because Mr. Rochester claimed my services without painful shame or damping humiliation.
Mr. Rochester loved me so truly, that Mr. Rochester knew no reluctance in profiting by my attendance: Mr. Rochester felt I loved Mr. Rochester so fondly, that to yield my attendance was to indulge my sweetest wishes.
One morning at the end of the two years, as I was writing a letter to Mr. Rochester dictation, Mr. Rochester came and bent over me, and said -- "Jane, have you a glittering ornament round your neck?"
I had a gold watch-chain: I answered "Yes."
"And have you a pale blue dress on?"
I had.
Mr. Rochester informed me then, that for some time Mr. Rochester had fancied the obscurity clouding one eye was becoming less dense; and that now Mr. Rochester was sure of one eye.
Mr. Rochester and I went up to London.
Mr. Rochester had the advice of an eminent oculist; and Mr. Rochester eventually recovered the sight of one eye.
Mr. Rochester cannot now see very distinctly: Mr. Rochester cannot read or write much; but Mr. Rochester can find Mr. Rochester way without being led by the hand: the sky is no longer a blank to Mr. Rochester -- the earth no longer a void.
When Mr. Rochester first-born was put into Mr. Rochester arms, Mr. Rochester could see that the boy had inherited Mr. Rochester own eyes, as they once were -- large, brilliant, and black.
On that occasion, Mr. Rochester again, with a full heart, acknowledged that God had tempered judgment with mercy.
My Edward and I, then, are happy: and the more so, because those My Edward and I most love are happy likewise.
